column726: If I am the first player  then my outcome is determined by the second player. There are two possible situations  | a.the second person has a absolute better choice. For example  choosing Y will give higher numbers  then I will chose the higher one in my table under the "Y" coloum  | b.the second person does not have absolute better outcome. Then I would think about  if I choose X  what would the fourth person choose to get higher outcome  and then the third and then the second. Then based on the second person's choice  to check my number  check whether it would give me higher number or not. |  | If I am the second player  I will use what the first person chose to guess the fourth person's choice   and then the third and then my own table. |  | The fourth person is the easiest.

I just tested out the possibilites and what I thought other people would choose. If you think about what other people would choose  then you could predict the amount of tokens you would get. Therefore  you can make the best decision with the highest probability of getting the most number of tokens.

Predicting the others' choices based on their options and the liklihood that they would choose the most preferable option. Understanding my own options and choosing the option that will lead to the most favorable outcome for myself.

The strategies I was using was to look at the next person and see what option I could take that would appeal to them  and also if they decided to be greedy (as most humans inherintly are)  I would choose the option of the two numbers that were less extremes of each other so if I did get "burned" by the person who came after me I wasn't taking as much of a gamble. If I came in first I'd try to look at the entire chain of events  and just because I had time and no points would be taken off for looking  the times when I came in first I tried to look out and get good options for the person who was put last since their decision linked back to mine. Also  I realized everyone here was smart enough to get into USC so they aren't easily distracted by a big number and will be able to work out what choice is the most beneficial to them as well.

If I were participating in a game like Display 7 and was the role Orange than I'd simply choose which ever option would yield the highest amount of token based of Red's chioce. If I were Green or Blue I'd work backwards from there to predict what the person after me would choose.

The starting player has to backtrack the most  firstly by giving the last player attractive choices  then continuing in reverse order of players until it comes back to player 1. If everyone does the rational choice of simply choosing whichever two choices pay higher and the payout for player 1 is acceptable  then that is the choice for player 1. Subsequent players have fewer choices to consider  but must always begin with what the last player would do with player 1's choice  in order to follow a similar thread of thought.

Looking at the last person to see what I think they will choose and working backwards | Looking for any obvious signs that someone might break the pattern that would get us all large amounts of tokens

i was able to predict all the results after a couple of matches based on what the first person in the order chose. from knowing that  i could determine what the last person would chose  and based on the last person i could determine the third person's choice  and from the third person's choice i could determine the second.
I looked at the decisions made prior to my turn and the potential decisions after my turn

I was intending to play off of other's selfishness. the fourth player is basically the player who determines the game.  I would first examine the second player because he would determine my outcome. from there I would jump to orange to see what he would choose in order to get blue's answer.  This allowed me to accurately assess what player would pick which choice with the exception of one round wherein I accidentally miscalculated.  Basically  any player who has a choice where there are 2 large numbers in one row will pick that row.  Any player who has larger numbers diagonal from eachother will examine the next player's numbers in order to determine what they must do to get the best outcome for themselves.  Once you figure out the thought process for one set  it does not matter who you are paired with  99% of the time they will think along the same lines.

I would decide what my highest payoff would be based on the choices the person after me would be likely to make. If I were the first turn  I would look at the last color to see what they would choose based on my highest payoff choice and then follow it back to what the person directly after me would most likely play. If I were last  I disregarded any moves but the first player's.

I looked at the payoff of the first which rationally determines the decision of the fourth which rationally determines the decision of the third which rationally determines the decision of the second which rationally determines the decision of the first.
